						<h2>
							New Forum progress.. 
							Saturday, December 13, 2003 - 4:28:22 PM
						</h2>
						<p>
							<P>I have a skeleton outline of the new forums programmed up.&nbsp; It`s workable, and is shaping up.. Right now there is thread listings, message viewing, new post page, reply page, forum list..&nbsp; There is still a ton of work mind you, but it`s going well.&nbsp; I am sneaking in some programming for the forums mostly at night, and with the holidays coming up I should have a bit of time too.</P>
<P>I am going to pick the features that I think are really usefull and implement them.. I am also going to scrap a lot of the features that I think are total fluff features (features that are worthless, just programmed in so the feature list looks good).&nbsp; From my conversations with people, most people want a lightweight, fast, organized and easy to use forum system that <STRONG>integrates seamlessly</STRONG> with their existing site.</P>
<P>If you want to to voice your opinions &amp; concerns regarding the new forums, post on <A href="http://forums.guildwizard.com/?f=21&amp;m=43108">this thread</A></P>
						</p>
					
						<hr />
					
						<h2>
							Turn off paging on Roster
							Thursday, December 11, 2003 - 3:55:39 PM
						</h2>
						<p>
							<P>Custom Rosters now have a configuration setting in their configuration panels to turn off paging for the roster grid.&nbsp; When you turn off paging, your roster will be one long list of everyone in the guild, as opposed to the 35 names per page.&nbsp; This is useful for when you are doing editing on the grid, looking to compare values etc.&nbsp; </P>
<P>Again, this is only on the Custom Roster. To change over to the custom roster, log in as an Admin/Officer account and click the custom roster button that is above the grid.&nbsp; You can switch back and forth between standard and custom roster btw.&nbsp; That was patched a few weeks ago, I dont think I reported it though :)</P>
<P>Still really busy with work, but sneaking in little patches like this here and there.</P>
						</p>
					
						<hr />
					
						<h2>
							Horizons + FFXI compatible - kinda 
							Wednesday, December 10, 2003 - 12:09:07 PM
						</h2>
						<p>
							<P>I programmed up the Horizons and FFXI components last month before I went to Jacksonville, but never did enable it on the signup.&nbsp; LoL, I won`t lie, I forgot about it until I went to check if Horizons was released yet :)&nbsp; </P>
<P>Anyway, Horizons and FFXI guilds can sign up and use GuildWizard.&nbsp; Now, let me be clear, I need help from guilds of these games to help me develop tools that will be usefull to these games.&nbsp; I intend on playing Horizons, it looks like a game that I can really get into (I can see my wife and clients cringing already !! :)&nbsp;&nbsp; However, no matter if I play or not, I can`t think of everything..&nbsp; I suspect a lot of people playing, also play EQ, and I know EQ people aren`t shy to give suggestions :)</P>
<P>Anyway, Horizons + FFXI guilds, signup for a free trial.. see what you like and what you don`t and maybe shoot me an email suggesting some things.&nbsp; </P>
						</p>
					
						<hr />
					
						<h2>
							Downtime today
							Tuesday, December 09, 2003 - 5:55:06 PM
						</h2>
						<p>
							<P>Today I brought down the main guildwizard server to transfer some database files to one of my new servers... I couldn`t have the service up while the files were transferring, because if someone made changes to their site that required database storage, it would have been lost when the database came online.&nbsp; </P>
<P>Those with Custom domains (<A href="http://www.yourguildname.com">www.yourguildname.com</A>) might have experienced about half an hour of downtime, because of my dumb Linux box which is my DNS server decided to not accept my DNS changes :)&nbsp; I checked everyones domains, and it should be ok.</P>
						</p>
					
						<hr />
					
						<h2>
							Forums moved to other server
							Sunday, December 07, 2003 - 12:55:49 PM
						</h2>
						<p>
							<P>I moved the forums to a new server... this new server is pretty much the same, hardware wise, as the other one.. just the bandwidth pipe is A LOT bigger.&nbsp; It`s connected to multiple OC3 connections.&nbsp; </P>
<P>Honestly, I don`t think the problem really is bandwidth as much as the forums are just not working the way they are implemented.&nbsp; I am swamped with work (5 web-applications on the go, and have about 1 month to get them all done!), so my guildwizard programming time is kind of slim right now... but I am going to write my own forums for sure.</P>
<P>Everyone is going to have to re-log into the forums to reset their cookie I think.</P>
						</p>
					
